snippet.textDisplay: As a former teacher, this could save a lot of time. However, the detailed commentary now expected from teachers isn't really there to help the kids. Many (perhaps most) kids don't read the comments and/or get frustrated when their work is covered by lots of comments. Also, marking work too frequently is unnecessary.  Thus covering work and exercise books with lots of comments is really an exercise in appeasing Ofsted and senior maanagement (who are trying to appease Ofsted).  In other words, these comments are so adults can tick boxes. Also, a savvy teacher can create labels with all the usual comments.. and then choose and stick the ones that suit.

snippet.textDisplay:
Good luck, James.
And this idea would be great for the disabled. So many ways I can use that, if made suitable for a paper printer too. If people are wondering yes I have hands but I have EDS type 3. When forced to write, my fingers fracture, causing horrible pain (you'd understand if you ever broken a bone) making them useless for weeks until the next time, I'm ambidextrous so favour (more like sacrifice) my left for writing as my right arm is more dominant and I need it for other tasks. Even chefs or kitchen staff can use it for labelling foods meaning no cross contamination from a pen. Hope he expands his idea as he can do a lot with it than just for teachers marking papers.
